Exploratory Data Analysis with R by Martin Welss

In this analysis I explore a dataset of white wine. Each observation contains a set of objective, mostly chemical tests and quality variable which is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts).

First, we load the dataset from the csv-file and get some statistical info about the dataset.

Univariate Plots Section

Quality is of course of primary interest because it is the variable we want to predict from the others, so we look at its histogram first.

Now the histograms of the potential “input” variables:

I think we can get a better impression of the quality distribution with frequency polygons:

The distributions of alcohol and quality resemble slightly so alcohol seems to be the best lead. We transform it to be a factor and remove the observations where alcohol.bucket is NA to get cleaner plots. I want to get a more detailed impression of alcohol.bucket, so I plot a histogram and a boxplot.

wine$alcohol.bucket <- cut(wine$alcohol, c(8,9,10,11,12,13,14))

wine <- subset(wine, !is.na(wine$alcohol.bucket))

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

It’s a tidy dataset where each variable is a column and each observation is a row. In this case, the dataset on white wines has 4898 observations of 13 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in the dataset is quality and how to predict it from the other variables.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

From the plots we see that the quality resembles a normal distribution. So we need to check the correlation between quality and the other variables. From the alcohol-quality boxplot we can see a trend that Quality increases with more alcohol, but the correlation does not convince me yet, this needs more investigation in the following sections.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, I created alcohol.bucket variable to get a feeling for the distributions of quality by alcohol and created also a corresponding boxplot.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The residual.sugar has a quite asymmetric distribution, the pH variable’s distribution has two peaks. Other than adding the alcohol.bucket variable, I needed the alcohol.bucket variable to create a boxplot of quality by alcohol and removed the records where alcohol.bucket was NA.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

Since we want to find the correlations between quality and the rest of the variables, I created some scatterplots and tested the correlation between promising quality-variable combinations. I had to deal with overplotting by adding transparency to the points. I carefully selected the alpha value so that the points of high quality observations are still visible. Furthermore I added in some plots a geom_smooth layer based on a linear model to see the correlation more clearly.

Because I could not find any convincing relation, I tried transformations of variables like the square fixed.acidity, the square root of pH and introduced a new variable prop.acidity followed by corresponding plots. But still no strong correlation could be found.

So I decided to test the some correlations numerically, but there is none greater than 0.5, which would have been a breakthrough.

cor.test(wine$quality, wine$alcohol)

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I found a slight linear relationship between pH and fixed.acidity where the fixed acidity decreases with increasing pH values.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship so far is between quality and alcohol, but with a correlation coefficient of 0.44 the correlation is not strong enough for a reliable prediction.

Multivariate Plots Section

We start with the strongest lead alcohol and quality but this time faceted by the different levels of alcohol using the alcohol.bucket variable.

I think I need quality to be a factor, so create it

wine$quality.factor <- factor(wine$quality)

I use jitter to get a better color impression.

pH seems to be a dead end, let’s try other variables.

We compute a new variable of promising candidates and create a corresponding plot.

wine$qmix <- wine$alcohol* 
  wine$total.sulfur.dioxide * 
  wine$fixed.acidity

Finally we test the correlation, but still not better than alcohol.

cor.test(wine$quality, wine$qmix)

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

To get a better impression of the relationship between quality and the other variables, I needed quality to be a factor. So I created a new factor variable from quality and used in the scatterplots to color the points. Overplotting was again to be dealt with and again I selected the alpha value so that the colors of the high and low quality observations stay visible. But there was no match winner revealed. I than created a new variable that was the product of three other variables that so far showed at least a little correlation with quality:

  • alcohol
  • total.sulfur.dioxide
  • fixed.acidity

The plot did not show a strong correlation, which was supported by the calculation of the correlation coefficient.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

What I found interesting was the relation between alcohol and quality over several other variables like pH or fixed acidity.The relation between alcohol and quality seems to be independent from the other variables since the higher quality points stay in the upper area of the plot. This supports a constant correlation between alcohol and quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Sine quality is the output variable that we try to predict from the other variables, I present as first plot the quality distribution faceted by alcohol, which so far has the strongest correlation with quality. We see that the first two subplots with the low levels of alcohol have their maximum at quality 5 whereas the following plots, the maximum moves to higher quality levels. I think this plot is important and quite interesting, because it gives a good impression of the relation between the quality and alcohol which is its strongest correlation. Very few wines have excellent quality and so have only a few wines a bad quality.

Plot Two

Description Two

The second plot is a scatterplot which shows clearly a linear correlation between quality and alcohol with the red line depicting the correlation. This supports the assumption that higher levels of alcohol correspond with higher quality. The plot also shows that the vast majority of vines have mediocre quality and only very few have the top level quality of 9 or a bad quality below 4.

Plot Three

Description Three

Plot three finally shows a scatterplot of alcohol by total sulfur dioxide colored by quality. I chose these three variables because they reflect the key characteristics of my analysis:

  1. alcohol and quality correlate
  2. total sulfur dioxide and quality correlate
  3. the colors of quality in the plot support that

We see the lighter colors of better quality in the upper areas, especially the purple points of high quality.

Reflection

I started off with histograms of the variables to get an overview of the distributions. Alcohol seemed most promising, so I wanted to create a boxplot. For that I needed alcohol to be a factor variable, so I used the cut function to create the alcohol.bucket variable. The boxplot then supported the relationship between alcohol and quality.

The bivariate analysis was somewhat sobering because no strong correlation could be found.To avoid overseeing a correlation I added to some of the plots a linear model smoother but no correlation was stronger than between alcohol and quality. Some slight correlation was found between sulfur dioxide, acidity and pH on the one hand and quality on the other hand. I created a new variable and tried transformations and combinations of the input variables.

The trend continued in the multivariate analysis.First I needed quality to be a factor, so I created a new variable for that. Then I used this factor variable to color some of the scatter plots. I finally created another variable the was the multiplication of alcohol, total.sulfur.dioxide and fixed.acidity. But no strong correlation surfaced.

Conclusion

I could not find a convincing correlation between quality and any of the other variables. I am pretty sure after my analysis, that there is at least no linear relationship. It could be a higher order relationship like exponential or polynomial, but I did not find any hints for that. So from my analysis I would conclude that there must exist other variables that correlate with quality of wine that were not in the dataset like the type of grape, geographical region, name of the vineyard or vintage. It would be most interesting to have those variables added to the dataset for a future analysis.

If I were a winemaker, I would probably be more interested in the relationship of the vintage and the quality before I start the wine press.
